  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1393034680" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1393034680" />
    <a title="Craig Pittman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4640029-craig-pittman"><img alt="Craig Pittman" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1465522554p2/4640029.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1393034680?book_show_action=true">Sep 15, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Craig Pittman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Craig Pittman" href="/user/show/4640029-craig-pittman">Craig Pittman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780684855882" href="/book/show/231113.Middle_Passage">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1393034680" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2038922951512240673">I finished this book a couple of days ago, but I have waited to review it until now because I couldn&apos;t figure out what to say about it. &quot;Middle Passage&quot; is a mishmash of styles and tropes, a mix of entertainment, erudition and enlightenment the likes of which I can&apos;t recall ever encountering before. I enjoyed it immensely and even snapped at someone for interrupting me when I was near the end. I wanted to see what happened. Yet the author&apos;s ultimate intent eludes me still.<br/><br/>The best part of the bo</span>
  <span id="freeText2038922951512240673" style="display:none">I finished this book a couple of days ago, but I have waited to review it until now because I couldn't figure out what to say about it. "Middle Passage" is a mishmash of styles and tropes, a mix of entertainment, erudition and enlightenment the likes of which I can't recall ever encountering before. I enjoyed it immensely and even snapped at someone for interrupting me when I was near the end. I wanted to see what happened. Yet the author's ultimate intent eludes me still.<br /><br />The best part of the book is the garrulous narrator and main character, freedman-turned-con man Rutherford Calhoun. A fatherless son, he's highly educated but low-caste. As the novel begins he's left his brother behind in his childhood home in Illinois and become a wandering rogue, living by his wits and his skill at picking a lock, and landed amid the gamblers, thieves and hookers of New Orleans in the 1830s. There he piles up debts he cannot pay and trifles with the affections of schoolmarm Isadora Bailey, who hopes to both reform and marry him. She traps him into marriage with the help of a ruthless black gangster -- but before they can march him down the aisle, Calhoun escapes by stowing away aboard a ship leaving port.<br /><br />And what a ship of fools it is. The Republic is bound for Africa to collect a cargo that includes 40 soon-to-be-slaves and one mysterious mystical entity. The captain, Ebenezer Falcon, is the quintessential 19th-century adventurer, a collector of fabulous artifacts and discoverer of ancient mysteries -- except he's also a dwarf and a pederast. We also get to know the first mate, tight-lipped, tightly wound New Englander Cringle, and the tough-cookie cook, Squibb. Up to this point the story is a straight-up picaresque, full of rude humor and gross characters.<br /><br />But then the ship reaches its destination and picks up its cargo, and things change. The slaves they've collected are from a tribe called the Allmuseri, wizardly warriors with a stylized form of combat and a lineage that suggest they were mankind's ancestors. The entity that accompanies them is their deity, which appears to warp time and space and sensibilities of anyone who gets too close to its crate.<br /><br />From here the book shifts gears as the crew plots mutiny, Falcon plots his counter-attack, the Allmuseri watch for their opportunity for revolt -- and all three take the conman into their confidence, expecting the confused Calhoun to take their side. The violence that follows, and the desperate scramble for survival that occupies the rest of the book, make for compelling reading -- and then, just when things seem as bleak as they can get, Johnson takes pity on the few remaining survivors and wraps up his story with an ending so hokey yet satisfying it might have come out of a movie rom-com. For a mere 209 pages, Johnson packs in a lot of action and adventure, along with plenty of philosophical discussion, mostly from Falcon.<br /><br />Calhoun's voice is what carries us through all this, a voice that's both archaic in tone yet modern in sensibility, one that's adept at orotund pronouncements and also the short-and-sweet punch line. It's also the voice of a man who's not only experienced at fooling other people but at fooling himself, yet who learns to see himself as clearly as he does everyone else around him. We learn, slowly, that he's telling us all this because he's keeping the ship's log, as the only person who knows the whole story, and the telling of the story is part of how he grows and changes too, finding where his loyalties lie at last, once he learns the truth about his own past.<br /><br />But is that all Johnson had in mind when he wrote this novel, which went on to win a National Book Award 25 years ago? Or was he reaching for something higher, deeper, greater than just the tale of how slavery was bad and sailors were mistreated and poorly paid? There are hints that what's going on here is designed to point out foibles of some modern day situations -- at one point Falcon sounds a little like a white CEO complaining about affirmative action, for instance. But to broaden it more plainly, I think, would have required broadening the novel's size too, and robbing its plot of its propulsive fascination. <br /><br />I guess, in the end, the question that counts most is: Was this a compelling read? The answer is: Yes. But maybe I'll come back and read it again in a few years and see if the meaning slips up on me like an Allmuseri warrior and smacks me upside the head a little more plainly.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2038922951512240673" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


