    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1415323843" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1415323843" />
    <a title="Kathy Kattenburg" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10268238-kathy-kattenburg"><img alt="Kathy Kattenburg" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1484365434p2/10268238.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1415323843?book_show_action=true">Oct 12, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kathy Kattenburg" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kathy Kattenburg" href="/user/show/10268238-kathy-kattenburg">Kathy Kattenburg</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1415323843" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11010319121316281360">The classic Quest novel, in this case about Rutherford Calhoun, a young man, freed from slavery by his dying master, who stows away on a ship which, it turns out, is a slaver bound for West Africa to pick up a load of human cargo. Calhoun starts out a petty thief and ne&apos;er-do-well who sees the ship as a way to escape his creditors and a marriage he doesn&apos;t want (more because he wants to continue his carefree bachelor life than because he doesn&apos;t love the woman). But during the course of the jour</span>
  <span id="freeText11010319121316281360" style="display:none">The classic Quest novel, in this case about Rutherford Calhoun, a young man, freed from slavery by his dying master, who stows away on a ship which, it turns out, is a slaver bound for West Africa to pick up a load of human cargo. Calhoun starts out a petty thief and ne'er-do-well who sees the ship as a way to escape his creditors and a marriage he doesn't want (more because he wants to continue his carefree bachelor life than because he doesn't love the woman). But during the course of the journey, he is transformed by the horrors of the Middle Passage endured by the enslaved Africans, as well as the brutality and physical and psychological rigors of life aboard commercial ships in the 1830s.<br /><br />Many reviews of this book have mentioned the odd narrative voice (which is supposed to be Calhoun's). And they are right: the narrative voice IS unsettling: It's more that of a post-civil rights, twentieth century African American intellectual (such as Charles Johnson!) than that of a freed slave in the 1830s. Also, the book is filled with anachronisms, such as Calhoun and another sea mate referring to the missing link between man and monkeys -- decades before Charles Darwin introduced the concept of evolution to the world. And Calhoun, at another point, musing about William Law, an obscure eighteenth century English cleric who wrote books about religion and mysticism. Also, a typically rough, rude, uneducated, working class sailor talking about Copernicus. Today, in a world where access to information is so democratized and global, sure. But on a slave ship in 1830? Unlikely.<br /><br />At first this weird narrative style bothered me. It's clear that the anachronisms are a deliberate choice -- this isn't about careless editing. But I couldn't figure out WHY Johnson had made this choice. And of course I still can't be sure what he had in mind. But one thing the narrative style does is universalize the story. Rutherford Calhoun is more than just this specific fictional character. In some sense, he is the voice of the collective consciousness by which the experience and history of an entire people reside in each individual. It makes sense that Johnson had something like this in mind, because the writing is infused with symbolic and metaphorical meaning. It has a surreal, magical cast to it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11010319121316281360" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

