<div id="review_985425596" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/985425596" />
    <a title="Angela Tyler" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19121942-angela-tyler"><img alt="Angela Tyler" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1600380955p2/19121942.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/985425596?book_show_action=true">Jul 03, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Angela Tyler" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Angela Tyler" href="/user/show/19121942-angela-tyler">Angela Tyler</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780684855882" href="/book/show/231113.Middle_Passage">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer985425596" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11996213257395673134">I just finished this amazing book, and all can say is that it is a good thing that I did NOT read it before I wrote <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/20932596.Queen_Mother' title='Queen Mother by Angela Norton Tyler' rel='nofollow noopener'>Queen Mother</a>. If I had, <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/231113.Middle_Passage' title='Middle Passage by Charles R. Johnson' rel='nofollow noopener'>Middle Passage</a> would have been all up in my head, messing with my story, disturbing my characters and whatnot! <br/><br/>I wouldn&apos;t have been able to tell my story with its fortuitous meetings and plot twists without thinking that I was somehow copying this voyage. I wouldn&apos;t have been able to write about the dignity of enslaved Africans without thinking about the All</span>
  <span id="freeText11996213257395673134" style="display:none">I just finished this amazing book, and all can say is that it is a good thing that I did NOT read it before I wrote <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/20932596.Queen_Mother" title="Queen Mother by Angela Norton Tyler" rel="nofollow noopener">Queen Mother</a>. If I had, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/231113.Middle_Passage" title="Middle Passage by Charles R. Johnson" rel="nofollow noopener">Middle Passage</a> would have been all up in my head, messing with my story, disturbing my characters and whatnot! <br /><br />I wouldn't have been able to tell my story with its fortuitous meetings and plot twists without thinking that I was somehow copying this voyage. I wouldn't have been able to write about the dignity of enslaved Africans without thinking about the Allmuseri. I wouldn't have been able to tell Canto's story without constantly thinking about Rutherford Calhoun. <br /><br />I would have compared my book to this one, and I would have been jealous.<br /><br />Luckily, I read <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/231113.Middle_Passage" title="Middle Passage by Charles R. Johnson" rel="nofollow noopener">Middle Passage</a> after writing my own story about the Middle Passage and, because of that, I was able to thoroughly enjoy it. True, I am a sucker for well-researched historical fiction and, one might argue, that this book errs on the side of being too well-researched. Really, how much do we need to know about nineteenth century ships... <br /><br />No, no, no! The detail is a sturdy scaffold that supports the plot and its larger-than-life characters. Isadora, Falcon, Papa, Squibb et al came alive because they walked through such a richly detailed world. It would have been a tragedy to plunk them down into a half-drawn picture and expect them to shine. <br /><br />A great story! <br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11996213257395673134" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


