    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1968920533" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1968920533" />
    <a title="Cheryl Durham" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24201324-cheryl-durham"><img alt="Cheryl Durham" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1392691231p2/24201324.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1968920533?book_show_action=true">Apr 11, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cheryl Durham" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cheryl Durham" href="/user/show/24201324-cheryl-durham">Cheryl Durham</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780684855882" href="/book/show/231113.Middle_Passage">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1968920533" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13400371585069620781">Charles Johnson did a phenomenal job with the Middle Passage. The main character, Rutherford Calhoun, a newly freed slave from Illinois, thought that he knew what he was running from (debt collectors and a refusal to marry) but not what he was running to. He boarded the Republic, and there, he learned that the ship was leaving New Orleans bound for Africa (bringing back slaves). Rutherford came to realize that his previous life (pickpocketing, womanizing and the like was nothing compared to what</span>
  <span id="freeText13400371585069620781" style="display:none">Charles Johnson did a phenomenal job with the Middle Passage. The main character, Rutherford Calhoun, a newly freed slave from Illinois, thought that he knew what he was running from (debt collectors and a refusal to marry) but not what he was running to. He boarded the Republic, and there, he learned that the ship was leaving New Orleans bound for Africa (bringing back slaves). Rutherford came to realize that his previous life (pickpocketing, womanizing and the like was nothing compared to what was ahead).<br /><br />Middle Passage, as we know from history, referred to the part of the trade where Africans were transported across the Atlantic to the West Indies. Here Johnson illustrates the conditions that the slaves endured during this terrible time in America's history (torn away from loved ones, densely packed quarters, disease, limited nourishment, some jumping over and others dying as well as other travesties). He also highlighted the many changes that occurred with the sailors (to include as oppose to exclude the thought of mutiny), the rough voyage (ship almost capsizing), dysentery, scurvy, the outbreaks of smallpox, starvation as well as cannalbalism.<br /><br />This book also highlighted how during this period a boy, Rutherford Calhoun, would become a man. He was able to bond with members of the Allmuseri tribe who were shackled, outwitted many of the sailors and the captain as well as others upon his return. The very person he was running from is who he would return to spend his remaining years. He was changed emotionally as well as physically.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13400371585069620781" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


